2.3. Relative entropy in UQ. The relative entropy, or Kullback--Leibler divergence, quantifies the discrepancy between two distributions (see, for example, [50, section A.5]). Given probability measures \gama  and \lambda , such that \lambda  \ll  \gama , the relative entropy of \lambda  with respect to \gama  is

\int  \scrR (\lambda  |  \gama ) =

log

d\lambda (y) d\gam a  (y)

\lambda (dy),

and we note that \scrR (\lambda  |  \gama ) \geq  0 with equality if and only if \lambda  = \gama  almost everywhere (the Gibbs inequality). For distributions that belong to a general exponential family, closed formulas exist for the relative entropy [28, 43]. For example, the relative entropy for d-dimensional multivariate Gaussian distributions \lambda  = \scrN  (\mu i, \Sigma i) and \gama  = \scrN  (\mu j, \Sigma j) is given by

(9)

