3.4. A posteriori computability. We emphasize that the components appearing in the argument of the optimization problem in (11), and in particular in the right-hand side of (26), are a posteriori computable quantities that represent significant computational savings over gradient approximations. Moreover, (26) incorporates worst-case scenarios that might not be efficiently observed using traditional estimates of the sensitivity. In the previous numerical experiment, we approximate (26) by

