In particular, we begin by fixing a data set for the nominal model \gama  by sampling, uniformly at random, 50 percent of the full data set depicted in Figure 6a. We then fit a squared exponential covariance model (20) using the maximum likelihood method. We also fit a collection of alternative models \{ \lambda 10, . . . , \lambda 100\} , where \lambda q is related to a geostatistical model that is fit using q percent of the full data set where a small number of points are added or deleted from the subset of data used for neighboring alternative models. For example, the data set used to construct \lambda 60 is formed by sampling 10 percent of the data points from the full

